text.tspan: Nothing or just CH called for
State 2, A+B, will hold as long as white is high and grey low
Mid position, CH + HW called for
State 3, B, will hold as long as grey is on
State 4, B, will hold as long as white is high
State 1: White off Grey off - Hot Water only
State 2: White on Grey off - Both
State 3: White on Grey On - Heating only
State 4: White off Grey On - hold in last position
If white and grey are both on (heating but no water) and
white goes off, grey will hold the motor at B for no good
reason. So, if white and grey are both on (heating only),
and we want to turn heating off, we have to turn grey
off (turn HW on) first, wait a bit, then turn both off.
Note: Grey is on when HW is off. White is on when CH is on.
A traditional controller uses three wires; a grey "HW off" wire that is powered when
HW is not called for; an orange "HW on"wire, and a white "CH on" wire. The valve contains
two microswitches. Switch 1 is activated when the valve reaches to the mid position
(hot water and heating both on), and Switch 2 when it reaches full extent (heating only)
